import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data_grouped = data.groupby('group')['pct'].mean().reset_index()
    data_grouped.sort_values('pct', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    
    plt.bar(data_grouped['group'], data_grouped['pct'])
    plt.xlabel('Income Range')
    plt.ylabel('Average Income Distribution')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the average income distribution across all states?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(data_grouped['group'], title='Income Ranges', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data_pivot = data.pivot_table(index='region', columns='group', values='pct', aggfunc='sum')
    data_pivot.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))

    plt.title("What is the income distribution by region?", wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel("Region")
    plt.ylabel("Percentage of Households")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title="Income Range", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Get the top 5 states with the highest total number of households
    top_5_states = data.nlargest(5, 'total')['name'].unique()

    # Filter the data for the top 5 states
    top_5_data = data[data['name'].isin(top_5_states)]

    # Create a pivot table with the income distribution for the top 5 states
    pivot_table = top_5_data.pivot_table(index='name', columns='group', values='pct')

    # Plot the horizontal bar chart
    ax = pivot_table.plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.title('What is the income distribution for the top 5 states with the highest total number of households?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of Households')
    plt.ylabel('State')
    plt.legend(title='Income Range', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Filter the bottom 5 states with the lowest total number of households
    bottom_5_states = data.nsmallest(5, 'total')['name'].unique()

    # Filter the data for the bottom 5 states
    bottom_5_data = data[data['name'].isin(bottom_5_states)]

    # Pivot the data to have income groups as columns and states as rows
    pivot_data = bottom_5_data.pivot_table(index='name', columns='group', values='pct')

    # Plot the horizontal bar chart
    ax = pivot_data.plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.title('What is the income distribution for the bottom 5 states with the lowest total number of households?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Percentage of Households')
    plt.ylabel('State')
    plt.legend(title='Income Range', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='group', y='pct', hue='name', data=data, ci=None)
    plt.title('What is the income distribution for each income range?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Income Range')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of Households')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='State', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
